column87:
I believe this guidance is lacking in research-intensive institutions. Many higher education (e.g., the U15) do not do a very good job of research data management because of the following reasons:
- No integrated tools exist.
- Institutional guidelines are not enforced.
- Most researchers 'do their own thing'.
- Many researchers are dependent on their teams to apply disciplined research data management hygiene.
- Many Research Ethics Boards (REBs) only engage 'for cause' and little proactive monitoring is performed.
- There is little automated support for agreement management. (e.g., Team NDAs, Collaborator Data-Sharing Agreements, and Participant Consent Forms)
- Engagement with internal IT teams to deliver data storage and/or tools is cumbersome - especially for distributed teams.

We believe DRA should partner with and commission relevant providers that can quickly deliver these kinds of platforms.
column88: We believe DRA should collaborate with us to commission the next-generation research data management platform for Canada. We have brought this idea forward to DRA and have demonstrated our ability to apply new emerging technology (blockchain) to effectively secure sensitive research data sharing.
column89:
Grants from DRA could fund the further development of features on our platform that all universities would benefit from. 

We believe a platform that could do the following provides a compelling leap forward for most research-intensive institutions:

- Fast research project initiation
- Simplified RLS engagement & support
- Integrated ARECCI Screening Tool and REB engagement & review
- Simplified team member, external collaborator, and research participant onboarding
- eSignature-enabled NDAs, Data-Sharing Agreements, and Consent Form management
- Data upload and sharing on CAC Data Center repository
- Granular data access control and management
- Tracking of all data management activities within a research project
- Realtime reporting and analytics
- Ability to transfer research data or subsets of data
- "Stealth project" capability
- Alerts and notifications for data archiving, retention, and deletion
- Virtual data room capabilities
- Advanced research computing
- Distributed peer reviews
- Ability to securely share and publish research data
- Ability to commercialize research data 

We believe that with some grant funding and in collaboration with DRA, this type of capability can be quickly and readily realized.
column90:
Very few existing research software platforms go beyond data storage with some limited search capabilities and tools.

Almost none deliver the following:
- Support for operational control of research data as described above.
- Support for stakeholder engagement as described above. (e.g., team members, external collaborators, and research participants)
- Support for data management after research conclusion (e.g., archiving, retention, and deletion)
- Ability to seamlessly publish research data.
- Ability to securely share research data using state-of-the-art encryption or web3 protocols.
- Ability to subscribe to published research.

myLaminin has brought a blockchain-enabled research data-sharing service to market that was researcher-designed. A product of a 3-month pilot with Queen's University at Kingston, it has been very well received and addresses many of the operational requirements mentioned above. 

A case study summarizing that pilot initiative can be found here: https://www.mylaminin.net/downloads

Queen's has now committed to a 12-month user validation phase that will no doubt enhance the service and give an opportunity to further increase the value proposition.

wow that's general and vague. No relationship to either software or research? it's basically saying that research software is anything that involves the intersection of any two or more of tools, disciplines, services, platforms, hardware, resources and people? I can think of a lot of things that meet that definition that are related to neither research nor software.

I'd define it as something more like digital tools used to conduct, enable, or facilitate some aspect of research, plus (maybe) the supports and services required to enable them to be used. 

I understand that you didn't want to exclude anything, but a definition that includes more things that don't belong to the specified domain than ones that do is not at all useful. 

Definitions need to exclude as well as include.  Or maybe you do mean to say that a hammer being used by a person as part of a home-repair service is research software?

column88: Plusieurs labos plus petit n'ont pas les moyens de garder des experts en logiciel de recherche dans leur domaine, neanmoins ils ont besoin de cette expertise de maniere ponctuelle pour poursuivre leur recherche. Par exemple, un labo de genomique a besoin de se construire un logiciel de suivi des mortalite / filiation /genetique des experiences. Leur besoin represente environ 4 a 6 semianes de travail d'un expert en logiciel. Le projet demande surtout des biologistes, et ils n'ont pas le financement pour faire effectuer le travail par un consultant. J'ai vu plusieurs histoires d'horreur de gaspillage de fonds publique avec des consultants ou des firmes privees engagees pour travailler sur des logiciels de recherche.

column77:
My comprehension of "research software": research (adjective) software (noun), therefore its definition should include the things that lives digitally and must exclude the aforementioned hardware, and people.

My comprehension of "software research": software (adjective) research (noun), in this case, it is the research itself and it should include the people, the activities, etc.

It makes sense to me to show a file, a process, or even a concept and tell that this is a research software, or this is part of a research software.
But it does not make sense to point at a disk, a cable or a person and tell that this is part of a research software. Software and hardware are concepts that were defined in opposition and to include one into the other would only cause confusion to an external observer.

column88: From my personal experience as a research software expert and previously researcher, the research software needs would be better served by creating an entity that would develop and support mainstream needs in the research community.
column89: An important issue with research software is that some field evolve quick and software need to be updated regularly. Short term grants tend to lead to software becoming obsolete by lack of support. Core software supported directly by the alliance would go a long way. Core open-source software need to be identified by domain and supported directly taking part of the load off the institutions and researchers.
column90: The current infrastructure force most researchers to directly produce their software which put a disproportionate load on smaller research labs and researchers that do not have an affinity with software development. This is possibly making research job less appealing for people that do not want to work as software developers.

column96: Grants allocated punctually are not sufficient to maintain and to ensure quality software for most institutions. A good share of software needs are shared by scientific domain and the software development is redundant between institution (some needs are specific, but some are shared). Maintaining some funding for small scale, ad hoc software development is required but large scale tools (Laboratory Information Management Software, Analysis software by domain, ...) would benefit from a centralized approach where individual institution would use shared and publicly maintained tools. Funding could be allocated as targeted software development and maintenance, but with a software that would be shareable and reusable. This would also allow the grouping of software developers with research expertise and help retain the knowledge they built in their respective fields by offering them salary grants cannot offer them.

column88: Attending to the needs of smaller players. We don't all need 100TB of server space, but we do need some storage, compute, and personnel support. Our research software needs are not eligible to be covered by SSHRC funds nor are they deemed scientific enough to be funded by CFI. Where does that leave us? Cobbling together limited term work study and co-op students and begging for support from our overstretched institutional research software team. This is fundamentally unsustainable, and it slows our work down incredibly. Our team and in fact all humanities in Canada are being significantly hampered by a lack of adequate and appropriate support.

column87: Training is useful for all aspects of the support described.   However, training alone without actual support is of limited value.   In particular, to offer training, staff must be experts.   It is a waste if they do not also offer actual support.  In addition, most training is not used -- the recipient just becomes aware of the approaches but is not an expert in it and does not have time to become one.   A particular issue is that faculty are not experts and cannot support a student who is willing to invest the time to learn more -- we need ways to support a graduate student (for example) becoming an expert.

column90: Canadian funding levels are too low to support programmers within research groups (i.e. a paid programming position).    Alliance can help via part time or limited time support for research groups.    As noted above, faculty are often not experts in software but they know their group (or a specific project, perhaps associated with a grad student) could benefit from more advance research software.   They key is to provide support to enable that -- something reliable that the grad student can rely on beyond the supervisor (e.g. a long term staff member working for the Alliance).
column96: Recognize that Canadian research groups are smaller (PI centric) and cannot support senior positions that other countries do (e.g. programmers or other long term research scientist positions).   If Canada is to be competitive and develop research tools and software we need to plug this gap.   The Alliance is one of the few ways this could be done.   Right now we have staff who are great but I would like to see them do more to support specific research groups and activities rather than focus mostly on training.    The training is great but I feel it could lead to so much more if support for specific projects were available afterwards.

I was disturbed at what was left out in above questions -- hardware,  HPC systems,  core libraries, compilers, debuggers, command line tools etc...
These are critical.   Expertise in these is critical.   If these break my research is not possible.   They come before everything else.
Canada must be competitive in high performance computing.   We are consistently behind but the distance is not too bad -- you can still compete.   Canada is about a factor of 2-3 smaller in HPC per capita than other G20 nations.  If Canada was much more behind (factor of 10) I would have to rethink my research program.   Alliance HPC systems are a critical component of maintaining research competitiveness in Canada because most universities have nothing (unlike other countries).  Without Alliance many science faculty hires would just not come to Canada.

The biggest help would be by improving the reliability of the various systems. There are far too many filesystem and internode communication issues which make the systems unusable for lengthy periods of time. The number of times we have messages going around our collaboration slack channel along the lines of "Is cedar broken for everyone, or just me?; Broken for me too.". I really fear the Alliance in its expansion drive is losing sight of what it really should be providing to users: reliable HPC computing facilities with clear futures and upgrade paths.

column89: My field has been significantly hindered by the lack of long-term funding for software developer/maintainer positions. There is a strong interest from the research community for common software tools, but very limited capability to develop them -- there are very limited funding opportunities to support hiring developers, and the funding that is available is almost always short/fixed term. The project I'm part of now is funded by a 5-year CFI grant: we've been able to develop many useful and popular tools, but have very limited ability to maintain them beyond the grant lifespan; we've also struggled a lot with staff retention. Since the grant is explicitly fixed term, developers and support staff are incentivized to "jump ship" to newer or longer term positions as soon as possible. Having some ability to create permanent positions would vastly improve development efficiency: software could be supported for longer, could be further developed to have more features and capabilities, more packages could be developed, and the loss of subject matter expertise could be significantly reduced.
column90: I think there's a gap in the form of career paths for subject-matter experts who develop research software. Research software needs a combination of software experts (those trained as developers) and subject-matter experts (those trained in the specific research area and also have basic/intermediate development skills). Software experts have a career path through industry, but subject-matter experts only career path is through pure/traditional academia which doesn't reward development work. Thus subject-matter experts are not rewarded for doing software work or development the skills to contribute to software work. We need a dedicated career path for trained academics to pursue research-related software development -- effectively permanent postdoc positions with explicit focus on software development and maintenance for the larger research community.

column77: Research software is written to support and carry out research, for examples simulation codes, data analysis and machine learning applications and libraries, automation scripts, and web portals for collaborative research and data sharing.  Research software experts combine software expertise with research knowledge to create or maintain research software defined in this way.   The definition of research software should thus not include other digital research technologies that it interacts with, e.g. it should not include hardware nor non-research specific software such as contact  management systems, communications systems, or account management.

column88:
One of our primary goals is to build the long term internal capacity for software development and delivery; as opposed to relying on external contractors that tend to have high associated costs, lack domain knowledge and are not available long term for troubleshooting etc. Longer term (2-5 years) innovation or maintenance funding opportunities help us achieve our goals. 

There are some components of software development (i.e. design) that are often best still done by contractors (e.g. design or discrete one-off projects) assistance identifying skilled contractors for tasks such as these would also be an area of potential support.

Fostering the adoption of our tools and resources is an important component after they have been developed.
